Project 2

Part 1

1) Reading the image

After making it in grayscale, We had the photo in Jpeg Format and got it with “readJPEG” command.The size of the array is 400 x 400 x 3 for the three dimensions. However, because it is a grayscale picture, all the 3 dimensions have the same value. Therefore, we will use only the first layer of the photo.

library(jpeg)
photo <- readJPEG("C:/Users/Hasancan/Desktop/photo.jpg", native = FALSE)

2) Finding Row Outliers

Initially, we got the first layer of photo to use it. Then, we calculated the mean and standard deviation of each row in order to find the upper and lower bounds. Afterwards, we checked the each pixel whether in the bounds or not. If they are out of bounds, we set their pixel value to 0 which changes their colour black. X-bar chart is used in this process, and the pixels are assummed to be normally distributed.

pic_original = photo[, ,1]
pic_part1 = photo[, ,1]

significance_level=0.001
for(i in 1:400){
  for(j in 1:400){
    row= pic_part1[i, 1:400]
    dist_mean = mean(row) #calculate mean of the each row
    dist_sd = sd(row) #calculate standard deviation of the each row
    upper_bound = dist_mean + qnorm((1-significance_level/2))*dist_sd #calculate upperbound for each row
    lower_bound = dist_mean + qnorm(significance_level/2)*dist_sd #calculate lowerbound for each row
    if(pic_part1[i,j]>upper_bound | pic_part1[i,j]< lower_bound){
      pic_part1[i,j]=0 #out of control pixels converted to black pixel
    }}}

#print image
par(mfrow=c(1,2))

plot(0.5:400.5,0.5:400.5,type="n", xlab = "Horizontal", ylab = "Vertical", main = "Original Image")
rasterImage(pic_original, 0.5,0.5, 400.5, 400.5,interpolate=FALSE)


plot(0.5:400.5,0.5:400.5,type="n", xlab = "Horizontal", ylab = "Vertical", main = "New Image")
rasterImage(pic_part1, 0.5,0.5, 400.5, 400.5,interpolate=FALSE)

Apparently, the number of outlier pixels are low because we use the significance level as 0.001. Moreover, the outliers in each row does not have any consistent pattern. As a result, we can say that the picture has pretty evenly distributed black and white pixels around the picture as it can be understood by looking at the picture itself.

3) Finding Column Outliers

In this part, we applied the same process as before. We calculated the mean and standard deviation of each column in order to find the upper and lower bounds. Afterwards, we checked the each pixel whether in the bounds or not. If they are out of bounds, we set their pixel value to 0 which changes their colour black. X-bar chart is used in this process, and the pixels are assummed to be normally distributed.

pic_part1 = photo[, ,1]

for(i in 1:400){
  for(j in 1:400){
    column= pic_part1[1:400, i]
    dist_mean = mean(column) #calculate mean of the each column
    dist_sd = sd(column) #calculate standard deviation of the each column
    upper_bound = dist_mean + qnorm((1-significance_level/2))*dist_sd #calculate upperbound for each column
    lower_bound = dist_mean + qnorm(significance_level/2)*dist_sd #calculate lowerbound for each column
    if(pic_part1[j,i]>upper_bound | pic_part1[j,i]< lower_bound){
      pic_part1[j,i]=0 #out of control pixels converted to black pixel
    }}}

#print image
par(mfrow=c(1,2))

plot(0.5:400.5,0.5:400.5,type="n", xlab = "Horizontal", ylab = "Vertical", main = "Original Image")
rasterImage(pic_original, 0.5,0.5, 400.5, 400.5,interpolate=FALSE)


plot(0.5:400.5,0.5:400.5,type="n", xlab = "Horizontal", ylab = "Vertical", main = "New Image")
rasterImage(pic_part1, 0.5,0.5, 400.5, 400.5,interpolate=FALSE)

The same arguments we proposed for the row version of the picture above are valid here as well. Particularly, We can observe more black pixels in the dark region on top left corner. However, apart from that the out of control pixels seem evenly distributed.

Part 2

1) Building a Regression Model

We try to build regression model by using patches to make prediction for center values of patches. We slided the windows by size 2. Therefore we have 175*175 patches for linear regression. Firstly, we created an empty matrix which is called variablesmall to store pixel values. After putting the values in that matrix, we built linear regression according to this matrix. Our dependent variables are the 1301st pixel in each patch and independet variables are the other pixels in each patch.

pic_part2 = photo[, ,1]

patch_size=51
count=0
n_patchessmall = 175 #Taking the window difference as 2



#empty matrix for dependent and independent variables
variablessmall = matrix(data = NA, nrow = n_patchessmall*n_patchessmall, ncol = 2601)


#take a patch with size 51*51 for small number of patches
for(i in 1:n_patchessmall){
  for(j in 1:n_patchessmall){
    
    patch = pic_part2[(2*i-1):(2*i+patch_size-2),(2*j-1):(2*j+patch_size-2)]
    patchrow=as.matrix(t(patch))
    count = count + 1
    
    variablessmall[count, ] = patchrow #the other pixels are put into the other 2600 columns
    
  }
}

datasmall=data.frame(variablessmall)
model=lm(X1301~.,datasmall)
rm(variablessmall)


plot(model$residuals)

qqnorm(model$residuals) # show that model is normal

The residual graph shows us the residuals are independently distributed around the mean 0. By this observations, we conclude that errors are identical and independently distributed. Also, errors have zero mean and constant variance according to the residual graph. The residual graph for all the pixels can be seen in part 3 below. QQnorm plot showed us the residual distrubited normally because there is a linear pattern in the QQ-plot. As a result, the assumptions for residuals in the regression are all satisfied. We can observe the residuals that are out of control by using X-bar chart.

2) Collecting all patches

To get whole residual values, we need to have all patches in the photo. Therefore, we get them by storing values in an empty matrix.

count=0
n_patches = length(pic_part2[,1])-patch_size+1
variables = matrix(data = NA, nrow = n_patches*n_patches, ncol = 2601)


for(i in 1:n_patches){
  for(j in 1:n_patches){
    #take a patch with size 51*51
    patch = pic_part2[i:(i+patch_size-1),j:(j+patch_size-1)]
    patchrow=as.matrix(t(patch))
    count = count + 1
    
    variables[count,  ] = patchrow #the other pixels are put into the other 2600 columns
    
  }
}
data=data.frame(variables)
rm(variables)

3) Predicting the pixel estimations and calculating residuals

We predict the 1301th values by using our regression model. Then, we calculate residuals for each pixel and plot them.

prediction1=predict(model,newdata=data[1:30000,])
prediction2=predict(model,newdata=data[30001:60000,])
prediction3=predict(model,newdata=data[60001:90000,])
prediction4=predict(model,newdata=data[90001:122500,])
prediction=c(prediction1,prediction2,prediction3,prediction4)
residual=prediction-data$X1301

plot(residual)

4) Extracting residual outliers

Finally, we found the lower and upper bound of residuals by calculating mean and standart deviation values and make the pixel values of outliers to 0.

significance_level=0.001

dist_mean = mean(model$residual)
dist_sd = sd(model$residual)
upper_bound = dist_mean + qnorm((1-significance_level/2))*dist_sd
lower_bound = dist_mean + qnorm(significance_level/2)*dist_sd

for(i in 1:350){
  for(j in 1:350){
    if(residual[(i-1)*350+j]>upper_bound | residual[(i-1)*350+j]< lower_bound){
      pic_part2[i+25,j+25]=0
    }}}

par(mfrow=c(1,2))

plot(0.5:400.5,0.5:400.5,type="n", xlab = "Horizontal", ylab = "Vertical", main = "Original Image")
rasterImage(pic_original, 0.5,0.5, 400.5, 400.5,interpolate=FALSE)


plot(0.5:400.5,0.5:400.5,type="n", xlab = "Horizontal", ylab = "Vertical", main = "New Image")
rasterImage(pic_part2, 0.5,0.5, 400.5, 400.5,interpolate=FALSE)

The pixels whose residuals are outliers can be seen as black dots in the picture above. It can be seen that the out of control residuals are accumulated around the dark regions. We can say that pixel values around these region cannot be estimated as accurately as the other pixels.

One of the reason behind this structure might be the autocorrelation between predictor pixels. This will result in biased estimator coefficents and standard deviations. As a result, the control limits on the X-bar chart for residuals will be affected. To get rid of this autocorrelation problem, we can model the linear model by using ARIMA technique. ARIMA models allow the user the get rid of the autocorrelation by differencing, autoregressive terms, and moving averages term. If we would like to resolve this problem, then we had to estimate the optimal ARIMA parameters (p,d,q) and frequency by using the auto.arima function. Then, we would create the model by using arima function. With this technique, the errors will be strongly independent and identically distributed and the control limits would be unbiased.
